1
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:34,743
 Henry V, King of England, and Charles VI, King of France 
signs the treaty of Troyes.

2
00:00:34,785 --> 00:00:39,414
The treaty states that the Kingdom of France will
belong to England upon the King's death.

3
00:00:39,456 --> 00:00:42,376
 But the two kings die a few months apart

4
00:00:42,417 --> 00:00:46,004
 Henry VI is the king of England and of France,
but he is only a few months old.

5
00:00:46,046 --> 00:00:49,508
Charles VII, the Dauphin of France, 
has no intenteion to abandon his kingdom to a child,

6
00:00:49,550 --> 00:00:51,802
nor even to his tutor, the Duke of Bedford.

7
00:00:51,844 --> 00:00:56,265
A bloody war begins and the English,
along with the Burgundians, invade France.

8
00:01:31,758 --> 00:01:33,760
Is anybody there?

9
00:01:35,262 --> 00:01:36,763
Jeanne.

10
00:01:40,267 --> 00:01:43,770
I'm always happy to see you, but to
keep coming twice, three times a day--

11
00:01:44,271 --> 00:01:46,773
- I need to confess.
- You already confessed this morning.

12
00:01:47,274 --> 00:01:48,775
I need to confess again.

13
00:01:49,276 --> 00:01:52,779
What terrible sin
have you committed since then...

14
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:54,781
that can't wait till tomorrow
to be forgiven?

15
00:01:56,283 --> 00:01:58,785
I saw a poor monk without shoes,
so I gave him some.

16
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:02,748
There's no sin in charity, Jeanne.

17
00:02:03,248 --> 00:02:04,750
- They weren't my shoes.
- Whose were they?

18
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:07,711
- My father's.
- I'm sure he'll forgive you.

19
00:02:09,213 --> 00:02:10,756
He already did.

20
00:02:11,256 --> 00:02:12,758
But I want Jesus
to forgive me too.

21
00:02:13,258 --> 00:02:15,761
If we were to ask forgiveness
all the time...

22
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:17,763
we'd spend our whole life
in church.

23
00:02:18,263 --> 00:02:21,725
- Is that bad?
- Well, no, but--

24
00:02:24,269 --> 00:02:26,772
- Are you happy at home?
- Oh, yes, very.

25
00:02:27,231 --> 00:02:29,775
And your mother?
Everything's fine with her?

26
00:02:30,275 --> 00:02:31,777
Yes, she's wonderful.

27
00:02:32,277 --> 00:02:34,780
And your sister, Catherine,
she's still your best friend?

28
00:02:36,281 --> 00:02:38,784
My sister's just--
She's wonderful.

29
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:42,746
And what about your other friends?
You don't like playing with them?

30
00:02:44,206 --> 00:02:45,749
Oh, yes.
I play with them, lots.

31
00:02:47,251 --> 00:02:49,753
Everything sounds wonderful.

32
00:02:51,255 --> 00:02:52,756
Yes, it is.

33
00:02:53,257 --> 00:02:54,758
Then why are you here so often?

34
00:02:57,261 --> 00:02:59,763
I feel safe here.
It's where I can talk to him.

35
00:03:02,266 --> 00:03:03,767
Him?

36
00:03:05,269 --> 00:03:06,770
Well, I try to talk to him...

37
00:03:07,271 --> 00:03:10,774
but mostly he's the one
who does the talking.

38
00:03:11,275 --> 00:03:14,778
Who is this ''he''?

39
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:19,783
He never says his name.

40
00:03:20,284 --> 00:03:23,745
What does he...

41
00:03:24,246 --> 00:03:25,747
look like?

42
00:03:31,253 --> 00:03:33,755
Beautiful.

43
00:03:37,259 --> 00:03:38,760
And what does he say to you?

44
00:03:40,262 --> 00:03:41,763
He says--

45
00:03:46,268 --> 00:03:49,771
He says--
He says I must be good...

46
00:03:51,273 --> 00:03:54,776
and help everyone
and take care of myself.

47
00:03:56,278 --> 00:03:57,779
Do you think he's coming
from the sky?

48
00:04:00,282 --> 00:04:01,783
Perhaps.

49
00:04:03,285 --> 00:04:06,747
But wherever he's coming from,
I think you should listen to him...

50
00:04:08,248 --> 00:04:10,751
'cause it sounds like
he's giving you very good advice.

51
00:04:36,276 --> 00:04:38,779
It's--
It's wonderful!

52
00:04:40,405 --> 00:04:40,906
It's wonderful.

53
00:05:59,401 --> 00:05:59,902
Jeanne.

54
00:10:05,814 --> 00:10:07,316
Mother!

55
00:10:13,822 --> 00:10:14,281
Catherine!

56
00:10:27,711 --> 00:10:29,171
Jeanne, are you all right?
Did they hurt you?

57
00:10:29,838 --> 00:10:31,340
I'm fine, really.

58
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:35,302
We've all been looking for you.
The English are everywhere.

59
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,304
- I was in the church.
- Really?

60
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:40,307
I was talking to the priest.
Do you know what he said to me?

61
00:10:40,224 --> 00:10:41,725
Burn over there!

62
00:10:42,184 --> 00:10:43,727
Tell me later.
Quick, hide in here.

63
00:10:46,230 --> 00:10:48,732
- Where are you gonna be?
- I'll be right here.

64
00:10:49,233 --> 00:10:49,733
I promise.

65
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:59,743
Well, that's what I call booty.

66
00:11:37,239 --> 00:11:38,740
Comrade.

67
00:11:54,214 --> 00:11:55,716
A woman with a sword.

68
00:11:58,969 --> 00:12:00,470
Look at this.

69
00:12:00,971 --> 00:12:03,473
Frenchmen are such cowards,
they've left all the fighting to women.

70
00:12:03,974 --> 00:12:07,477
If that's God's will,
then so be it.

71
00:12:07,978 --> 00:12:11,481
Fine with me.
I love women.

72
00:12:34,963 --> 00:12:36,465
Hold still, bitch.

73
00:12:36,965 --> 00:12:38,467
How can I do it
if you keep wriggling about?

74
00:13:30,978 --> 00:13:31,478
Your turn now.

75
00:14:04,970 --> 00:14:07,472
God, preserve and bless the soul
of this, our dearly departed.

76
00:14:07,973 --> 00:14:10,475
Keep us safe from fear and sin.
Amen.

77
00:14:17,983 --> 00:14:18,483
Come on.

78
00:14:58,982 --> 00:15:00,484
Listen, Jeanne.

79
00:15:00,984 --> 00:15:04,488
Your aunt and uncle are gonna take you
to their house for a couple of weeks...

80
00:15:04,988 --> 00:15:07,491
just to give us time
to rebuild things here.

81
00:15:15,958 --> 00:15:17,459
You understand?

82
00:16:27,988 --> 00:16:29,489
Lord, we give thanks
for the food you've given us.

83
00:16:29,990 --> 00:16:31,491
Teach us always
to love this land...

84
00:16:31,992 --> 00:16:34,453
and to save it from those
who seek to destroy it.

85
00:16:34,953 --> 00:16:36,455
- Amen.
- Amen.

86
00:16:59,978 --> 00:17:01,480
So, good night, then.

87
00:17:08,987 --> 00:17:13,492
- What's going to happen to her?
- She'll be fine.

88
00:17:13,992 --> 00:17:17,454
She'll grow up, find a good man,
make him some children. Don't worry.

89
00:17:17,955 --> 00:17:19,456
She's been hurt, but she'll survive.

90
00:17:19,957 --> 00:17:22,459
Tomorrow she'll be
as right as rain.

91
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:24,461
You'll see.

92
00:17:28,966 --> 00:17:30,467
I want to see a priest.

93
00:17:53,991 --> 00:17:57,452
- Why did she have to die?
- Only God can answer that.

94
00:17:57,953 --> 00:18:01,456
I know Jesus says
to love your enemies, but I can't.

95
00:18:01,957 --> 00:18:05,460
I just want the English
to burn in hell forever and ever!

96
00:18:06,962 --> 00:18:09,464
I realize your anger, Jeanne.

97
00:18:09,965 --> 00:18:11,466
But we must learn to forgive.
It's hard...

98
00:18:11,967 --> 00:18:15,429
but revenge will never
bring about peace.

99
00:18:15,971 --> 00:18:18,473
What will?
And what will bring her back?

100
00:18:18,974 --> 00:18:22,477
And why did she have to die
in the first place instead of me?

101
00:18:22,978 --> 00:18:24,479
Why didn't He take my life
instead of hers?

102
00:18:24,980 --> 00:18:27,441
It was my fault!
I was late!

103
00:18:27,941 --> 00:18:32,487
She gave me her hiding place!
Why did He save me?

104
00:18:32,988 --> 00:18:35,490
Calm down, Jeanne.
Calm down.

105
00:18:38,911 --> 00:18:41,455
I don't pretend
to know God's will...

106
00:18:41,955 --> 00:18:44,458
but one thing I am sure:

107
00:18:44,917 --> 00:18:48,462
The Lord always has a good reason.

108
00:18:48,962 --> 00:18:52,466
Perhaps He chose you because
He needs you...

109
00:18:52,966 --> 00:18:54,468
for some higher calling.

110
00:18:54,968 --> 00:18:57,429
As long as you answer that call...

111
00:18:57,930 --> 00:19:01,475
your sister will not
have died in vain.

112
00:19:01,975 --> 00:19:04,436
I don't want to wait
for His call.

113
00:19:04,978 --> 00:19:06,480
Be patient.

114
00:19:06,980 --> 00:19:08,482
I want to be with Him always.

115
00:19:08,982 --> 00:19:12,486
Soon you will be able to take part
in your Holy Mass.

116
00:19:12,986 --> 00:19:15,489
When you eat of His flesh
and drink of His blood...

117
00:19:15,989 --> 00:19:17,491
you will be at one with Him.

118
00:19:17,991 --> 00:19:21,411
I want to be at one with Him now.

119
00:19:28,377 --> 00:19:29,920
So, what did he say?

120
00:19:30,712 --> 00:19:32,214
He says we must bring her to church
whenever she wants.

121
00:19:33,674 --> 00:19:36,218
Easy for him. He's not the one
who has to do the bringing.

122
00:19:36,718 --> 00:19:38,220
Come on.
This is important.

123
00:19:38,720 --> 00:19:41,223
We mustn't let her out of our sight.

124
00:19:41,723 --> 00:19:45,227
Don't worry. I will watch her
like my own shadow.

125
00:20:34,735 --> 00:20:37,237
I want to be at one with You now.

126
00:21:09,728 --> 00:21:11,230
A message for the dauphin of France.

127
00:21:21,740 --> 00:21:22,241
A message.

128
00:21:32,709 --> 00:21:35,212
Captain, a message for the dauphin.

129
00:21:35,671 --> 00:21:37,214
I'll take it.

130
00:21:44,721 --> 00:21:46,223
The dauphin!
The dauphin!

131
00:22:00,696 --> 00:22:04,241
Louis. Louis. Hey.
Shouldn't you be learning your lessons?

132
00:22:04,741 --> 00:22:06,243
I don't want to learn.
I want to fight.

133
00:22:07,703 --> 00:22:10,205
You will. But for now, you must
at least learn to wipe your nose.

134
00:22:15,711 --> 00:22:16,211
A letter for His Majesty.

135
00:22:21,717 --> 00:22:25,179
Another one from this girl
calling herself the Maiden of Lorraine.

136
00:22:25,721 --> 00:22:28,223
I can read for myself,
you know?

137
00:22:28,724 --> 00:22:31,185
She pretends she's been sent by God.
Charlatans.

138
00:22:31,685 --> 00:22:33,228
It's a pity there isn't enough wood
to burn them all.

139
00:22:34,730 --> 00:22:36,231
- She says she'll be here tomorrow.
- You mustn't see her, My Lord.

140
00:22:37,691 --> 00:22:40,235
We know nothing about her. We don't
even know if she's from Lorraine.

141
00:22:40,736 --> 00:22:42,237
What difference does it make
where she comes from?

142
00:22:43,739 --> 00:22:45,240
If she comes from Burgundy,
it makes a difference.

143
00:22:45,741 --> 00:22:47,242
It might be a trap.
Look, signed ''X.''

144
00:22:47,743 --> 00:22:49,203
What sort of a name is ''X''?

145
00:22:49,703 --> 00:22:52,206
Or must we assume that a messenger
of God can't even write her own name?

146
00:22:52,706 --> 00:22:55,209
My Lord, Trémoille is correct.
She says she hears voices.

147
00:22:55,709 --> 00:22:58,212
She may be a sorceress,
a witch.

148
00:22:58,712 --> 00:23:01,215
Regnault, you see witches everywhere.

149
00:23:01,715 --> 00:23:03,217
She's just a peasant.

150
00:23:04,718 --> 00:23:07,221
A peasant who cares about her king.

151
00:23:07,721 --> 00:23:11,225
All she wants is to see me crowned
and permission to fight for me.

152
00:23:11,725 --> 00:23:15,229
Not exactly. She wants you
to give her an army at your expense.

153
00:23:15,729 --> 00:23:18,232
Bearing in mind your mother stole every
last piece of gold in the treasury...

154
00:23:19,733 --> 00:23:21,235
I fail to see how you can afford
such an adventure.

155
00:23:21,735 --> 00:23:23,237
I can see her if I want to.

156
00:23:27,741 --> 00:23:29,243
After all, with half of France
in the hands of the English...

157
00:23:30,702 --> 00:23:31,203
what have I got to lose?

158
00:23:31,703 --> 00:23:32,204
The other half.

159
00:23:32,704 --> 00:23:35,207
You mustn't see her,
Your Majesty.

160
00:23:35,707 --> 00:23:37,209
She may be an instrument
of the devil.

161
00:23:37,709 --> 00:23:39,211
Well, I think you should.

162
00:23:46,718 --> 00:23:47,219
Well, here's an amusing situation.

163
00:23:48,720 --> 00:23:51,223
I would love to know why my devoted
mother-in-law thinks one thing...

164
00:23:51,723 --> 00:23:55,227
and my two most loyal
and trusted advisors...

165
00:23:55,727 --> 00:23:57,229
think precisely the opposite.

166
00:23:57,729 --> 00:24:01,233
Because I care about you.
Come here.

167
00:24:12,703 --> 00:24:15,205
Your health and happiness has always
been my first concern, Charles...

168
00:24:15,706 --> 00:24:17,207
ever since you were a little boy.

169
00:24:17,708 --> 00:24:19,209
And I think I know you
better than your own mother.

170
00:24:19,710 --> 00:24:21,211
You think so, eh?

171
00:24:21,712 --> 00:24:24,214
Yes.

172
00:24:24,715 --> 00:24:27,217
I know, for example,
the sickness that plagues your heart.

173
00:24:27,718 --> 00:24:30,220
I know how painful it is
for you to have loved a father...

174
00:24:30,721 --> 00:24:34,224
without ever knowing
if he was really yours.

175
00:24:36,727 --> 00:24:38,228
Do I know you enough? Hmm?

176
00:24:40,731 --> 00:24:43,233
What has that got to do
with this maiden?

177
00:24:43,734 --> 00:24:47,237
Who better than a messenger from God
to give answers to your questions?

178
00:24:48,739 --> 00:24:51,241
You think she was sent from God?

179
00:24:51,742 --> 00:24:53,243
You're a fine judge
of character, Charles.

180
00:24:53,702 --> 00:24:56,205
It'll take you less than five minutes
to expose her if she's a fake.

181
00:24:57,706 --> 00:25:00,209
But if she's not...

182
00:25:02,711 --> 00:25:04,213
then she will give you
your answers...

183
00:25:07,716 --> 00:25:09,218
and place the crown on your head.

184
00:25:12,721 --> 00:25:15,224
With respect to my lady, I think it's
going to take more than a peasant girl--

185
00:25:15,724 --> 00:25:18,227
I'm not interested
in what you think, Trémoille...

186
00:25:18,727 --> 00:25:19,228
or even what I think.

187
00:25:19,728 --> 00:25:22,231
It's what simple people think
that matters, and the fact is that...

188
00:25:22,731 --> 00:25:28,237
simple people up and down this country
are already talking about her.

189
00:25:28,737 --> 00:25:30,239
Now, you know
what simple people are like--

190
00:25:30,739 --> 00:25:33,242
always ready to believe
any old prophecy.

191
00:25:37,704 --> 00:25:39,206
Like this one...

192
00:25:39,706 --> 00:25:42,209
about a virgin from Lorraine...

193
00:25:42,709 --> 00:25:45,212
saving France.

194
00:25:49,716 --> 00:25:51,218
And now...

195
00:25:52,719 --> 00:25:55,222
this girl comes along...

196
00:25:55,722 --> 00:25:57,224
from Lorraine.

197
00:25:58,725 --> 00:26:02,229
And suddenly, there's a spark
of hope in their simple minds.

198
00:26:10,737 --> 00:26:12,239
You shouldn't disappoint them.

199
00:26:12,739 --> 00:26:16,243
If they believe in her--

200
00:26:16,702 --> 00:26:19,204
if she can put back
the fire in our army--

201
00:26:20,706 --> 00:26:22,207
then I believe in her too.

202
00:26:38,724 --> 00:26:39,224
Stop it!

203
00:26:42,728 --> 00:26:44,229
Louis, be quiet for once.

204
00:27:02,706 --> 00:27:05,209
- She's coming, Your Majesty.
- All right.

205
00:27:05,709 --> 00:27:06,210
Calm yourself.

206
00:27:07,711 --> 00:27:10,214
Your Majesty, I urge you
not to see this woman.

207
00:27:10,714 --> 00:27:12,216
It all reeks of a Burgundian trap.

208
00:27:12,716 --> 00:27:16,220
My astrologers assure me the timing
is propitious: Leo with Virgo rising.

209
00:27:16,720 --> 00:27:20,224
Have you never noticed
on the astrological chart...

210
00:27:20,724 --> 00:27:22,226
that the virgin
is next to the lion?

211
00:27:22,726 --> 00:27:24,228
Supposing she's an assassin?

212
00:27:25,729 --> 00:27:28,232
My-My-My dear Trémoille...

213
00:27:28,732 --> 00:27:30,234
I'm not even king yet.

214
00:27:30,734 --> 00:27:32,236
Who would want to assassinate me?

215
00:28:24,705 --> 00:28:27,207
She's arrived, My Lord.
She's in the guards' room.

216
00:28:27,708 --> 00:28:28,208
Fine, fine.

217
00:28:32,713 --> 00:28:35,215
I suppose I shall have
to make a decision.

218
00:28:45,726 --> 00:28:47,227
Why is life so complicated?

219
00:28:49,730 --> 00:28:51,231
Sometimes I really wish
I could be someone else.

220
00:28:54,735 --> 00:28:56,236
That's a good idea, sire.

221
00:29:00,073 --> 00:29:01,575
What do you mean?

222
00:29:02,075 --> 00:29:04,536
Let someone else
pretend to be you.

223
00:29:05,037 --> 00:29:07,539
And see if she can find me?
That's a brilliant idea.

224
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:10,542
If she's really been sent by God,
she'll discover the trap.

225
00:29:11,210 --> 00:29:13,712
And if she's an assassin,
she'll kill the wrong man. Brilliant.

226
00:29:25,933 --> 00:29:27,434
- Mother?
- Not now.

227
00:30:21,113 --> 00:30:23,615
I have come to see the dauphin.

228
00:31:17,294 --> 00:31:17,794
Who are you?

229
00:31:21,048 --> 00:31:21,673
I'm - I'm --

230
00:31:21,924 --> 00:31:26,428
His most gracious majesty,
Charles de Valois...

231
00:31:26,678 --> 00:31:28,180
dauphin of France.

232
00:31:47,991 --> 00:31:50,494
I can see you are a good man.

233
00:31:50,994 --> 00:31:51,495
But you're not the dauphin.

234
00:31:56,959 --> 00:31:59,461
I'm sorry to insist,
but I must see the dauphin.

235
00:31:59,962 --> 00:32:02,464
We have no time to lose.
Where is he?

236
00:32:04,967 --> 00:32:08,470
He's here.
Find him yourself.

237
00:32:35,956 --> 00:32:38,458
Now you'll see
who'll pass for a king.

238
00:33:51,990 --> 00:33:54,451
There's no need to be afraid, sire.

239
00:33:56,995 --> 00:33:57,496
I'm not the king.

240
00:33:58,956 --> 00:34:02,459
I know you're not yet,
but you will be soon.

241
00:34:15,973 --> 00:34:17,432
Out. Out.

242
00:34:19,977 --> 00:34:21,478
How did you know who I am?

243
00:34:21,979 --> 00:34:23,480
- Her voices, of course.
- ''That's him,'' they said.

244
00:34:23,981 --> 00:34:26,483
''The one in the corner
with the big nose.''

245
00:34:33,991 --> 00:34:34,491
Back off!.

246
00:34:39,955 --> 00:34:41,415
Oh, my gentle dauphin.

247
00:34:50,966 --> 00:34:52,467
I have a message...

248
00:34:52,968 --> 00:34:55,470
from the King of Heaven...

249
00:34:55,971 --> 00:34:57,472
for you.

250
00:34:59,975 --> 00:35:01,476
You only.

251
00:35:10,986 --> 00:35:12,487
Follow me.

252
00:35:13,989 --> 00:35:15,490
Your Majesty, I really think --

253
00:35:15,991 --> 00:35:20,495
My dear loyal Trémoille,
I know I can count on you...

254
00:35:20,996 --> 00:35:22,456
to - to ensure our privacy.

255
00:35:22,956 --> 00:35:25,459
I need to talk to her alone.

256
00:35:30,923 --> 00:35:33,467
He needs to talk to her alone.

257
00:35:33,967 --> 00:35:35,469
Fine.

258
00:35:52,986 --> 00:35:54,488
I was about ten years old.

259
00:35:54,947 --> 00:35:57,491
It was a beautiful spring day.

260
00:35:57,991 --> 00:35:59,493
I was taking a shortcut home
through the forest...

261
00:35:59,993 --> 00:36:04,456
when a strange wind...

262
00:36:04,957 --> 00:36:06,416
began to blow.

263
00:36:14,967 --> 00:36:18,470
It was such a strange sound,
almost like words...

264
00:36:18,929 --> 00:36:20,430
calling me.

265
00:36:40,993 --> 00:36:42,494
The second time...

266
00:36:43,954 --> 00:36:45,455
was many years later.

267
00:36:45,956 --> 00:36:49,459
I was coming back from church,
when suddenly...

268
00:36:49,960 --> 00:36:51,461
the same...

269
00:36:51,962 --> 00:36:55,424
violent wind.

270
00:37:00,971 --> 00:37:02,472
Then...

271
00:37:03,974 --> 00:37:06,476
a shape...

272
00:37:06,977 --> 00:37:08,437
appeared...

273
00:37:10,981 --> 00:37:12,482
in the middle of the sky.

274
00:37:12,983 --> 00:37:15,485
The shape...

275
00:37:15,986 --> 00:37:16,486
of...

276
00:37:18,989 --> 00:37:19,489
of a man.

277
00:37:33,962 --> 00:37:37,466
Everything was moving so fast.
So fast.

278
00:37:40,969 --> 00:37:41,470
The wind, the clouds.

279
00:37:43,972 --> 00:37:46,475
I couldn't move.
I couldn't breathe.

280
00:37:47,976 --> 00:37:51,480
I was so frightened.

281
00:37:52,981 --> 00:37:54,483
He was...

282
00:37:55,984 --> 00:37:56,485
so...

283
00:37:56,944 --> 00:37:58,445
so...

284
00:37:59,988 --> 00:38:01,490
here.

285
00:38:11,959 --> 00:38:13,460
And then I knew
that God had chosen me.

286
00:38:13,961 --> 00:38:17,464
But I did not understand
what it was He wanted me to do.

287
00:38:17,965 --> 00:38:21,426
What was my mission?
What could I do to help my country?

288
00:38:21,927 --> 00:38:24,471
But how? I was nothing.
I was just a poor girl.

289
00:38:24,972 --> 00:38:29,476
I did not know anything about--
about making war or riding.

290
00:38:29,977 --> 00:38:33,438
So I decided to wait...

291
00:38:33,939 --> 00:38:36,483
and not to speak of it
to anybody.

292
00:38:36,984 --> 00:38:38,485
You did well.
You did well.

293
00:38:38,986 --> 00:38:41,488
I didn't wait long.

294
00:38:42,990 --> 00:38:47,452
I was going to Mass,
like I do every day...

295
00:38:48,996 --> 00:38:50,455
and the same...

296
00:38:51,957 --> 00:38:54,459
strange wind--

297
00:39:22,946 --> 00:39:25,490
Everything was made clear.

298
00:39:27,993 --> 00:39:29,494
God had given me a message.

299
00:39:31,955 --> 00:39:33,457
A message to deliver.

300
00:39:36,960 --> 00:39:39,463
What--

301
00:39:39,963 --> 00:39:41,465
What was the message?

302
00:39:49,973 --> 00:39:52,476
He said...

303
00:39:52,976 --> 00:39:56,480
that I must save France
from her enemies...

304
00:39:56,980 --> 00:39:59,441
and bring her back
into the hands of God.

305
00:39:59,942 --> 00:40:02,486
And He told me that I...

306
00:40:02,986 --> 00:40:04,488
Jeanne...

307
00:40:04,988 --> 00:40:07,491
will lead you
to the altar at Reims...

308
00:40:10,994 --> 00:40:12,454
where you will be crowned...

309
00:40:14,957 --> 00:40:15,457
the king...

310
00:40:21,964 --> 00:40:22,464
of France.

311
00:40:46,989 --> 00:40:48,448
- Sire, are you --
- I'm fine.

312
00:40:51,994 --> 00:40:54,496
This is, in fact, Jean d'Aulon,
my loyal friend and finest archer.

313
00:40:54,955 --> 00:40:57,457
I put her in your care.

314
00:40:57,958 --> 00:41:00,419
Find her suitable lodgings
here in the castle...

315
00:41:01,962 --> 00:41:02,462
and guard her with your life.

316
00:41:03,964 --> 00:41:06,466
Sire, I won't be needing any lodgings
if we're to be marching on Orléans.

317
00:41:06,967 --> 00:41:08,468
Orléans has held out
for six months...

318
00:41:08,969 --> 00:41:11,471
so I don't suppose a few days more
will make much difference.

319
00:41:11,930 --> 00:41:12,431
Take some rest.

320
00:41:20,981 --> 00:41:22,482
Put the bags here.

321
00:41:24,943 --> 00:41:26,486
Please accept my apologies...

322
00:41:26,987 --> 00:41:29,489
for me pretending
to be the -- you know.

323
00:41:29,990 --> 00:41:31,491
Do you think
that I can have some water?

324
00:41:31,992 --> 00:41:34,494
Water. Yes, of course.

325
00:41:34,995 --> 00:41:36,413
Would you get some water?

326
00:41:36,914 --> 00:41:38,457
- Anything else?
- I need to see a priest.

327
00:41:38,957 --> 00:41:42,461
- Now?
- Yes. I didn't confess today.

328
00:41:43,962 --> 00:41:48,425
All right.
Raymond, a priest.

329
00:41:48,926 --> 00:41:49,426
Anything else?

330
00:41:49,927 --> 00:41:51,470
I shall also be needing
a new war horse...

331
00:41:51,970 --> 00:41:54,473
a sword, armor...

332
00:41:54,973 --> 00:41:57,476
and an artist
to make a banner for me.

333
00:41:57,976 --> 00:42:00,479
- Now?
- Better today than tomorrow.

334
00:42:00,938 --> 00:42:02,439
This might take a little time...

335
00:42:02,981 --> 00:42:06,485
but let me see what I can do.

336
00:42:06,985 --> 00:42:10,489
Oh! I shall also be needing someone
who can read and write.

337
00:42:10,989 --> 00:42:12,491
This I can do.

338
00:42:12,991 --> 00:42:15,494
I was studying at the University
of Paris until the English invaded it.

339
00:42:15,994 --> 00:42:18,455
- I thought you were an archer.
- Yes, I am.

340
00:42:18,956 --> 00:42:23,460
I'm an archer who can read and write.
Who do you want to write to?

341
00:42:23,961 --> 00:42:25,420
The king of England.

342
00:42:27,965 --> 00:42:30,467
I want to give him the chance
to leave in peace...

343
00:42:32,970 --> 00:42:35,472
before I get to Orléans.

344
00:42:43,939 --> 00:42:44,439
Dunois.

345
00:42:44,940 --> 00:42:48,443
- What?
- A big one, straight at us.

346
00:42:51,947 --> 00:42:52,447
What side?

347
00:42:52,698 --> 00:42:54,199
Window side.

348
00:43:10,340 --> 00:43:10,841
What?

349
00:43:12,342 --> 00:43:14,845
I have wonderful news, finally.

350
00:43:15,345 --> 00:43:17,848
He is sending her to us.
Thanks be to God. We're saved.

351
00:43:18,348 --> 00:43:18,849
It's--
It's wonderful.

352
00:43:19,308 --> 00:43:21,810
Calm yourself, Xaintrailles.
Who has finally done what?

353
00:43:22,311 --> 00:43:25,814
The dauphin. He's sending us
food and supplies and an army...

354
00:43:26,315 --> 00:43:28,817
led by Jeanne,
the maiden from Lorraine.

355
00:43:29,318 --> 00:43:30,819
Isn't it wonderful?

356
00:43:31,320 --> 00:43:32,821
Yes, it's a miracle.

357
00:43:37,326 --> 00:43:39,828
I can't believe
they are sending a woman.

358
00:43:41,330 --> 00:43:43,832
I wonder what color dress
she'll be wearing.

359
00:43:45,334 --> 00:43:45,834
Blue.

360
00:43:47,336 --> 00:43:49,838
With a blue ribbon in her hair
to tie up Talbot.

361
00:43:53,342 --> 00:43:56,845
Does anyone know if
she even knows how to ride a horse?

362
00:43:57,346 --> 00:43:57,846
She knows.

363
00:44:12,319 --> 00:44:12,819
Were you sent by Lord Dunois?

364
00:44:13,320 --> 00:44:15,822
Yes, we were.

365
00:44:16,323 --> 00:44:18,825
- Where are the English?
- Everywhere. Where's the food?

366
00:44:19,326 --> 00:44:20,827
It's coming.
I rode on ahead.

367
00:44:22,329 --> 00:44:24,831
I have a message
for the captain of the English army.

368
00:44:25,332 --> 00:44:25,832
- His name is Talbot.
- I know.

369
00:44:26,333 --> 00:44:29,837
- Can you take me to him?
- He's on the other side of the river.

370
00:44:30,337 --> 00:44:32,840
So, who gave the order for me
to be brought to this side of the river?

371
00:44:35,342 --> 00:44:38,846
Hey, my friend. It's good
to see your ugly damn face again.

372
00:44:39,346 --> 00:44:41,849
- La Hire, I'm warning you. Don't swear.
- Sorry, Jeanne.

373
00:44:42,349 --> 00:44:46,812
Let me introduce the king's
half-brother, the dogged Lord Dunois.

374
00:44:48,313 --> 00:44:50,816
Lord Dunois, will you show me
to the other side of the river?

375
00:44:51,316 --> 00:44:53,819
Wait. Wait!

376
00:44:57,322 --> 00:44:59,825
Fine! Go now, if you want!
But not with me!

377
00:45:00,325 --> 00:45:03,829
You may have a duty to God,
but I have a duty to my people.

378
00:45:04,329 --> 00:45:06,832
And my people are starving.

379
00:45:07,332 --> 00:45:09,835
Right now, I'm going to take
the food back to the city.

380
00:45:10,335 --> 00:45:12,838
And if you can please calm down
and let me accompany you to Orléans...

381
00:45:13,338 --> 00:45:14,840
it will be my honor
to welcome you.

382
00:46:14,316 --> 00:46:16,818
Jesus Christ.

383
00:46:17,319 --> 00:46:18,820
The goddamn English
will pay for this.

384
00:46:19,321 --> 00:46:22,824
Yes, they will, and so will you
if you don't stop swearing.

385
00:46:41,343 --> 00:46:43,846
Come on. I'm happy
to welcome you in my tavern.

386
00:46:44,346 --> 00:46:45,848
Come on in.

387
00:46:49,309 --> 00:46:50,811
La Hire, Gilles,
let me show you something.

388
00:47:00,320 --> 00:47:02,823
Tourelles are around here.
The river crosses there.

389
00:47:07,327 --> 00:47:10,831
Calm down.
You can't blame those people.

390
00:47:11,331 --> 00:47:12,833
They've been hearing
about you for weeks.

391
00:47:13,333 --> 00:47:15,836
There's nothing to hear!
And why is there nothing to hear?

392
00:47:16,336 --> 00:47:17,838
Because I haven't done anything!
And why haven't I?

393
00:47:19,339 --> 00:47:20,841
'Cause none of you
will listen to me!

394
00:47:26,346 --> 00:47:27,848
Why don't you join us?

395
00:47:29,308 --> 00:47:30,809
We're about to discuss
the campaign.

396
00:47:33,312 --> 00:47:34,813
I'm sorry.

397
00:47:35,314 --> 00:47:36,815
So from here,
Talbot has spread his forces...

398
00:47:37,316 --> 00:47:38,817
between these forts up here.

399
00:47:39,318 --> 00:47:41,820
But in the last few days it seems,
according to our scouts...

400
00:47:42,321 --> 00:47:44,823
that some troops have been
deployed to this fort here.

401
00:47:45,324 --> 00:47:45,824
What about this huge pile down here?

402
00:47:47,326 --> 00:47:48,827
That's the Tourelles.
The English were planning...

403
00:47:49,328 --> 00:47:51,830
to launch an attack from it,
but then we broke down the bridge--

404
00:47:52,331 --> 00:47:54,833
- I did.
- Yeah.

405
00:47:55,334 --> 00:47:56,835
Which should keep them quiet
for a while.

406
00:47:57,336 --> 00:47:59,838
Now, my hunch is...

407
00:48:00,506 --> 00:48:02,007
the attack will come
from St. Loup, here.

408
00:48:02,966 --> 00:48:05,469
And what does Jeanne think?

409
00:48:06,970 --> 00:48:09,473
I don't think.
I leave that to God.

410
00:48:09,973 --> 00:48:12,434
I am nothing in all of this.
I'm just the messenger.

411
00:48:13,310 --> 00:48:13,810
So...

412
00:48:14,311 --> 00:48:15,812
what is the message?

413
00:48:16,563 --> 00:48:20,067
We give the English...

414
00:48:20,567 --> 00:48:22,069
a last chance
to go home in peace.

415
00:48:22,569 --> 00:48:24,071
And if they refuse?

416
00:48:24,571 --> 00:48:25,072
If they refuse...

417
00:48:28,575 --> 00:48:30,077
we recross the river...

418
00:48:31,578 --> 00:48:34,081
and attack here...

419
00:48:34,581 --> 00:48:35,082
at the Tourelles.

420
00:48:37,584 --> 00:48:40,087
That makes no sense at all.
The Tourelles is virtually impregnable.

421
00:48:40,587 --> 00:48:44,091
If we are on the other side of the river
attacking the Tourelles...

422
00:48:44,591 --> 00:48:47,094
what's to stop Talbot
attacking the city from the north?

423
00:48:47,594 --> 00:48:51,098
- God.
- God. Why, of course.

424
00:48:51,598 --> 00:48:55,060
We'd forgotten about Him.

425
00:48:57,563 --> 00:49:02,067
I feel a great sorrow for you
because you are laughing now...

426
00:49:02,568 --> 00:49:05,070
but by tomorrow night,
some of you will be dead.

427
00:49:05,571 --> 00:49:08,073
With respect, we can't just
attack the Tourelles like that.

428
00:49:08,574 --> 00:49:11,076
- It's a very complicated matter.
- What's so complicated about it?

429
00:49:11,577 --> 00:49:16,081
All you have to do is what you're told.
What could be simpler than that?

430
00:49:16,582 --> 00:49:18,083
I am the drum...

431
00:49:18,584 --> 00:49:20,085
on which God is beating out
His message.

432
00:49:20,586 --> 00:49:23,088
He's beating it so hard,
it's bursting my ears!

433
00:49:23,589 --> 00:49:26,091
You have to understand,
it's not easy for us.

434
00:49:26,592 --> 00:49:29,094
I mean, for our pride
to suddenly be usurped by--

435
00:49:34,558 --> 00:49:38,061
Well, with all due respect,
by a--

436
00:49:38,562 --> 00:49:40,063
by a girl.

437
00:49:45,569 --> 00:49:47,070
So that's it.

438
00:49:47,571 --> 00:49:52,075
To you, I'm just a girl.

439
00:49:53,577 --> 00:49:58,081
Put yourself in my shoes for a moment.
How would you feel if you were me?

440
00:49:58,582 --> 00:50:01,084
Knowing what I know...

441
00:50:01,585 --> 00:50:04,087
enormous gratitude.

442
00:50:08,592 --> 00:50:10,093
One hell of a girl, huh?

443
00:50:16,558 --> 00:50:18,060
I warned you.

444
00:50:22,564 --> 00:50:26,068
I do love her when her fire
gets well and truly stoked.

445
00:50:26,568 --> 00:50:28,070
Me too.

446
00:50:30,572 --> 00:50:32,074
Hello, my friends!

447
00:50:33,575 --> 00:50:35,077
What a journey.

448
00:50:35,577 --> 00:50:37,079
But we made it.

449
00:50:38,580 --> 00:50:40,082
Back together again.
Let's have some fun.

450
00:50:44,586 --> 00:50:47,089
Fine.
I shall look like a man.

451
00:50:53,595 --> 00:50:55,097
Stop it!

452
00:50:55,597 --> 00:50:58,058
How dare you stop me
from doing God's will!

453
00:50:58,559 --> 00:51:00,060
He didn't tell you
to cut all your hair off!.

454
00:51:00,561 --> 00:51:02,062
How dare you tell me
what God tells me to do!

455
00:51:02,563 --> 00:51:05,065
Whatever! But since He's not going
to come down and cut it Himself--

456
00:51:05,566 --> 00:51:07,067
At least let someone
cut it properly!

457
00:51:10,571 --> 00:51:12,072
Raymond, bring the scissors.

458
00:51:12,573 --> 00:51:15,075
Louis, fetch the mirror.

459
00:51:19,580 --> 00:51:21,081
Stop getting so angry about everything.
Calm down.

460
00:51:21,582 --> 00:51:25,085
I am calm!
It's God that's angry.

461
00:51:25,586 --> 00:51:28,088
I need to send a letter, now.

462
00:51:28,589 --> 00:51:29,089
Fine.

463
00:51:29,590 --> 00:51:32,092
''To you, Henry, king of England...

464
00:51:32,593 --> 00:51:36,096
and to you, Duke of Bedford,
who call yourself regent of France...

465
00:51:36,597 --> 00:51:40,058
obey the King of Heaven
and abandon your siege.

466
00:51:40,559 --> 00:51:43,061
Give back the keys
to the other towns you've taken...

467
00:51:43,562 --> 00:51:45,063
and go back home
to your island.

468
00:51:46,565 --> 00:51:49,067
To you, Lord Talbot, I beg you
as humbly as I can beg you...

469
00:51:49,568 --> 00:51:52,070
for the sake of the lives
of your soldiers...

470
00:51:52,571 --> 00:51:54,072
do not bring about
your own destruction.

471
00:51:54,573 --> 00:51:58,076
Surrender to me, Jeanne the maiden,
who wassen there by God. ''

472
00:52:01,580 --> 00:52:03,081
Message!

473
00:52:03,582 --> 00:52:06,084
''But if you do not
heed my warning...

474
00:52:06,585 --> 00:52:08,086
then we shall raise
such a battle cry...

475
00:52:08,587 --> 00:52:10,088
as there has not been heard in France
for a thousand years. ''

476
00:52:19,598 --> 00:52:22,059
Sire, message.

477
00:52:22,559 --> 00:52:25,062
''This is the third and last time
I will write to you.

478
00:52:25,562 --> 00:52:27,064
If you are still here at noon,
I warn you...

479
00:52:27,564 --> 00:52:30,067
you will hear from me
to your very great destruction.

480
00:52:30,567 --> 00:52:33,070
Please give me your answer
speedily. ''

481
00:52:34,571 --> 00:52:35,072
Go fuck yourself!

482
00:52:38,575 --> 00:52:40,077
What did they say?

483
00:52:40,577 --> 00:52:44,081
They said
they'll think about it.

484
00:52:45,582 --> 00:52:47,084
Good.

485
00:52:47,584 --> 00:52:50,087
To be honest,
I don't think they'll leave tomorrow.

486
00:52:54,591 --> 00:52:56,093
I can't wait for tomorrow.

487
00:53:24,580 --> 00:53:26,081
French blood is spilling.

488
00:53:30,586 --> 00:53:33,088
Wake up! Hurry!

489
00:53:36,592 --> 00:53:38,093
They've started the battle
without me.

490
00:53:44,558 --> 00:53:47,060
There's a battle to fight
and a war to be won.

491
00:53:51,565 --> 00:53:52,065
Damn.

492
00:53:57,571 --> 00:53:58,071
Sound the retreat!

493
00:54:00,574 --> 00:54:02,075
My banner.
My banner!

494
00:54:09,583 --> 00:54:10,083
Open the gate!

495
00:54:23,597 --> 00:54:26,099
What happened?
Who gave the order to attack?

496
00:54:26,558 --> 00:54:29,061
God knows.
It was a bad idea.

497
00:54:29,561 --> 00:54:31,063
Were the men confessed?
Where are the priests?

498
00:54:31,563 --> 00:54:34,066
We didn't take them.
We wanted to make a surprise attack.

499
00:54:34,566 --> 00:54:36,068
Dunois, was it you
who gave the order to attack?

500
00:54:38,570 --> 00:54:40,072
- Answer me!
